node.text:
Some of my go-tos! Enjoy 😊 

Greek Inspired Salad Jar
* 1-2 cups kale
* 1 tbsp feta cheese
* 4oz chicken thighs 
* 10 olives 
* ¼ cup red onion 
* ½ orange bell pepper 
* ½ cup chickpeas
* 1 tbsp balsamic

BLT Remix Salad jar 
* 1 cup mixed greens
* 2 pieces nitrate free bacon
* 2 eggs 
* ½ cup cucumber 
* 1 cup tomatoes 
* 2 tbsp paleo ranch

Veggie Goddess
* 1 cup mixed greens
* ½ cup red onion 
* ½ cup black beans 
* ½ cup quinoa
* ½ cup cucumber 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Tex Mex Jar Combo 
* 1 tbsp cilantro 
* 2 cup lettuce   
* 4oz ground turkey or grass-fed ground beef
* ½ cup corn
* ¼ cup onion 
* ½ cup bell peppers 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Coconut oil pulling benefits:
Fights bad breath,
improves gum health &
maintains teeth whitness.

What to do:
Step 1: Swish 1 tbsp coconut oil in your mouth for 10-15 min (yes min!) Step 2: Spit in trash afterwards since oil will clog the drains
Step 3: Brush your teeth normally after and floss like you normally would.

Cheers to great oral health!
Xoxo
Amanda

Of course the fruits, veggies, nuts, seeds, etc are the most nourishing with their fiber, vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, and phytonutrients. They should be the daily go to snacks.⁠

node.text:
Healthy Carbs to Incorporate in Your Diet! (Swipe to see more)⁠
⁠
Carbs like rice, quinoa & potatoes can have a beneficial effect on energy levels, digestion, athletic performance, & are a great source of minerals and fiber. Carbs have gotten a bad rap lately but really the truth is you just need to find the right amount daily for you. Some things to take into consideration when judging how many carbs you should incorporate in a day include your activity levels, insulin sensitivity, & your overall goals 😁⁠
⁠
Details on each below:⁠⁠
⁠
Potato - a great source of vitamins, minerals, & antioxidants. They also contain resistant starch which may help reduce insulin resistance, which can help improve blood sugar control & helps feed gut bacteria.⁠
⁠
Sweet potatoes- rich in fiber, vitamin C, vitamin A, manganese & antioxidants. They’re delicious baked, roasted, boiled, or sautéed.⁠
⁠
White rice - is actually brown rice with the germ and bran removed. Despite a common misconception, the macronutrient & calorie contents are relatively the same. Some fiber & most nutrients are stripped away during the refining process, leaving it with very few essential nutrients. However, it contains less arsenic, is easier to digest, & is great for refueling muscles with glycogen post-workout, which is one of the reasons why a lot of athletes choose it over brown rice.⁠
⁠
White rice also has a much higher glycemic index of 89 while brown rice has a GI of 50. This can be significant to diabetics and those with insulin resistance. If you’re active & you’re not insulin resistant, you definitely don’t have to be overly concerned w/ glycemic index, especially in a balanced diet.

Brown rice - full of minerals like phosphorus, manganese, selenium & magnesium. It also contains antioxidants that help protect the body from oxidative stress. 🤗⁠

Quinoa - provides all 9 essential amino acids, making it a complete protein! It’s a wonderful source of fiber which helps you feel full longer, & in turn possibly help with weight loss. Quinoa is also a good source of minerals like iron, magnesium, manganese, zinc, & more.⠀⁠ 
⁠
Ultimately quinoa,  brown/white rice, & potatoes are nutritious choices.

Always something special about visiting my dad’s childhood country, Austria 🇦🇹⁠⁠
⁠⁠
My husband, Chris and I are starting to make a tradition of visiting our heritage countries every other year if we can (He’s Italian & I’m Austrian).⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Here are some of my favorite things about Austria:⁠⁠
🌲 The nature here is unbelievable⁠⁠
🍲 I love how fresh the food & dairy is⁠⁠
🐄 There are plenty of animals around to pet⁠⁠
🕺 The people here are super friendly⁠⁠
💪 My fit Uncle Patrick & my uncle Peter usually take us on epic hikes or go rock climbing with us⁠⁠
👩‍👩‍👧‍👦 Alway amazing to reconnect with my aunts, uncles & cousins in Austria⁠⁠
❤️ Love seeing my dad in his element, laughing & having a good time⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I sometimes forget how truly amazing it is to get the opportunity to experience other cultures! What are some of your favorite places to visit?⁠⁠
⁠⁠
xoxo,⁠⁠
Amanda⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#austria #vacation #family

How to build an EPIC toast 🍞 ⁠ (Swipe to see toast making ideas) ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The key to creating a healthy & delicious toast combination is getting creative with your layers. First, I recommend going for a more nutritious bread like sourdough or sprouted Ezekiel bread since their nutrients are more bio-available & intact when compared to something like plain white bread. There are also some good paleo breads out there for those trying to limit grains or with a gluten-intolerance.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Next, choose a base layer like yogurt, hummus, etc. for your toast along with your favorite toppings & extras! These are so great because you can really pack in extra nutrients and customize the toast to be your ideal combo.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Sharing some more info on 5 of my favorite combinations below:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Cottage Cheese Pear:⁠⁠
-Ezekiel bread, toasted ⁠⁠
-Pear, sliced ⁠⁠
-Honey⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Almond Banana Chip:⁠⁠
-Ezekiel bread, toasted ⁠⁠
-2 tbsps almond butter Almond Butter ⁠⁠
-Banana, sliced ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp Chocolate Chips ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Chia Berry Yogurt Parfait:⁠⁠
-Ezekiel bread, toasted ⁠⁠
-¼ cup Greek yogurt + stevia ⁠⁠
-Strawberry slices ⁠⁠
-2 tbsps Blueberries ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp Chia seeds ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Loaded Avocado:⁠⁠
-Sourdough toast ⁠⁠
-1 Avocado, mashed ⁠⁠
-1 Hard boiled egg ⁠⁠
-5-6 Radish slices ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Garden Fresh:⁠⁠
-Sourdough toast ⁠⁠
-2 tbsps hummus ⁠⁠
-Grape tomatoes, halved ⁠⁠
-Cucumber slices ⁠⁠
-Balsamic glaze⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What to do: ⁠⁠
1- Toast your bread. ⁠⁠
2- Add your base layer to the toast. ⁠⁠
3- Top with your favorite fruits and veggies along with any extras for added flavor. ⁠⁠
4- Enjoy!⁠⁠
⁠⁠

Here’s to building a well rounded routine 🏋️‍♀️ ⁠
⁠
Part of the reason I emphasize strength training so much is because I used to be an absolute cardio addict. While I still incorporate cardio a lot into my routine, I’ve noticed how much better I feel overall by making some form of strength training a priority in my weekly routine.⁠
⁠
Whether you’re using strength training to compliment a running routine or cardio to compliment a strength program, it’s crucial to support your body in a variety of ways.⁠
⁠
Another thing I do notice is people tend to overdo cardio when their goal is fat loss. That’s another reason I emphasize weights and that you definitely don’t want to overtrain nor do you need a ton of cardio to hit your fat loss goals. Overtraining or doing an insane amount of cardio could definitely result in an injury or feeling run down and I want to make sure you’re feeling good and your body is well supported.⁠
⁠
Lastly, I personally notice that I feel better when incorporating yoga once a week. Mobility, yoga or stretching can definitely also help to prevent injury and support healthy movement in other parts of your routine.⁠
⁠

node.text:
Make time for you ❤️ Because you deserve to feel your best.⁠⁠
—⁠⁠
The default state of any organism is health. And it doesn’t come from some fringe diet. It doesn’t come from a cross-fit regimen. It doesn’t come from a supplement. And it doesn’t come counting calories. These are all tools and should be used as such but the primary variable is you. What are you doing every day to create habits that will lead you to your best, most optimal self? It doesn’t have to be all or nothing—as long as you’re progressing daily (and this could be in terms of your diet, the scale, your lifts, your sleep quality, or even your mindset) you’re on the right path.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁠⁠
Also, this shouldn’t be taken to imply that by doing everything “right” (i.e. some illusory notion of perfection) that illness is completely avoidable. Definitely not so. Genes and, to be honest, luck also play a part and for that we have modern medicine. But when it comes to lifestyle conditions, by far the most common ailments affecting humans today, the research is clear: we do have a say.⁣⁠⁠
—⁠⁠
Caption by my friend @MaxLugavere⁠⁠
Image by Unknown (DM me or comment for credit)⁠⁠
—⁠⁠
I share this post with you out of the love and compassion of my heart. Making yourself a priority too is not selfish, it’s necessary.⁠⁠
xx,⁠⁠

What’s your drink of choice? ☕️ 🍵 ⁠
⁠
Whether you’re a matcha lover or coffee addict, it’s great to get a gauge of where your caffeine level is landing. While there’s no guide to where you should exactly land, if you notice yourself feeling extra jittery, anxious or cracked out, that may be a sign you’re overdoing it in the caffeine arena. The amount can also vary wildly per brand so make sure to check in with yourself & how you’re feeling. ⁠
⁠
For people more sensitive to caffeine, matcha and green tea can often be a great choice not just because of the often lower caffeine levels but the L-Theanine found in these drinks that can help to balance out the jittery feeling often associated with caffeine while still helping to improve focus & energy. ⁠
⁠
Lastly, herbal teas are a great way to enjoy a delightlful drink without adding extra caffeine to your day.⁠
⁠
Reminder that caffeine levels will vary by amount and brand so double check with your local coffee shop or brand sourced if you’re looking for the exact amount of caffeine in your drink.⁠
⁠
*Average amounts listed for: 12oz nitro, 12oz cold brew, 12oz coffee, 1 espresso shot, 1 teaspoon of matcha mixed w/ 12oz hot water, 1 bag black tea, 1 bag green tea, 1 bag herbal tea*⁠
⁠
Inspired by @collegenutritionist⁠
⁠

Sugar is hidden in more foods than many are aware of!⁠
⁠
That’s why it’s more important now than ever to become an informed consumer. It’s up to you to take matters of your health into your own hands.⁠
⁠
The book @sugarproofkids by Michael L. Goran, PhD is a great deep dive into all things sugar and what you can do about it.⁠
⁠
One key takeaway is that while a lot of sugars are similar, fructose is a the type of sugar you’ll want to minimize overall when it’s not paired with the appropriate fiber.⁠
⁠
Fructose found in fruit is encapsulated in a fiber-rich flesh which helps to slow the absorption down, making it a lighter load on your liver.⁠
⁠
High fructose corn syrup, agave nectar and fruit juice concentrates are all examples of sweeteners with a higher concentration of fructose that you’d want to minimize overall.⁠
⁠
Remember that the most important thing is paying attention to your total sugar load for the day and when you can opt for whole fruit over added sugars 😘⁠
⁠
